      <h1>A Complete Guide to Tipping in the United States</h1>
      <p class="article-intro">Tipping in the U.S. can feel confusing, especially if you did not grow up with the custom. This guide covers who you should tip, how much to leave in every common situation, and a few mental math shortcuts so you never have to pull out your phone at the table.</p>
    </header>

    <AdUnit slot="blog-top" format="horizontal" />

    <TableOfContents />

    <h2>Why Tipping Exists in the U.S.</h2>
    <p>Unlike most countries, the United States allows employers to pay tipped workers a lower base wage. As of 2026, the federal tipped minimum wage is $2.13 per hour, though many states set it higher. Tips are not a bonus — they make up the majority of a server's income. Whether or not you agree with the system, stiffing your server means they effectively worked your table for free.</p>
    <p>That context matters because it shapes the expectation: tipping is not optional at sit-down restaurants. It is a core part of how service workers are compensated.</p>

    <h2>Standard Tip Percentages by Service</h2>

    <h3>Restaurants (Sit-Down)</h3>
    <p>The accepted range is <strong>15% to 20%</strong> of the pre-tax bill. Fifteen percent signals adequate service; 20% is the norm for good service. For truly outstanding experiences, some diners leave 25% or more.</p>
    <p>At a counter-service or fast-casual restaurant where you order at the register, tipping is appreciated but not expected. A dollar or two, or 10%, is generous.</p>

    <h3>Bars</h3>
    <p>The standard is <strong>$1 to $2 per drink</strong> for beer, wine, or simple mixed drinks. For elaborate cocktails that take real skill and time, tip $2 to $3 per drink, or 15–20% of your tab if you are running one.</p>

    <h3>Food Delivery</h3>
    <p>Tip <strong>15% to 20%</strong> of the order total, with a minimum of $3 to $5. Delivery drivers use their own vehicles and pay for their own gas, so the tip is their primary compensation. If the weather is bad or the order is large, lean toward the higher end.</p>

    <h3>Rideshare (Uber, Lyft)</h3>
    <p>A tip of <strong>15% to 20%</strong> is appropriate. For short rides under $10, a flat $2 to $3 is reasonable. If the driver helped with luggage, navigated difficult conditions, or made a long trip, tip on the higher side.</p>

    <h3>Hotel Housekeeping</h3>
    <p>Leave <strong>$2 to $5 per night</strong> on the desk or pillow with a note that it is for housekeeping. Leave the tip daily rather than at checkout, because different staff may clean your room each day.</p>

    <h3>Hair Salons and Barbers</h3>
    <p>The standard is <strong>15% to 20%</strong> of the service cost. If you received a wash, cut, and color totaling $150, a $22 to $30 tip is appropriate. Tip each person who provided a service — if an assistant washed your hair, a few dollars for them is a nice gesture.</p>

    <h3>Other Services</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Valet parking:</strong> $2 to $5 when your car is returned</li>
      <li><strong>Hotel bellhop:</strong> $1 to $2 per bag</li>
      <li><strong>Taxi drivers:</strong> 15% to 20% of the fare</li>
      <li><strong>Movers:</strong> $20 to $50 per person for a full move</li>
      <li><strong>Grocery delivery:</strong> 10% to 15%, minimum $5</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How to Calculate a Tip Quickly</h2>
    <p>You do not need a calculator for most situations. Here are two fast methods.</p>

    <h3>Method 1: Double the Tax</h3>
    <p>In many U.S. states, sales tax falls between 7% and 10%. Doubling the tax gives you a rough 14% to 20% tip, depending on your local rate. If your tax line says $6.40, leaving $12.80 gives you approximately an 18% tip in a state with 7% tax. It is not precise, but it is fast and close enough.</p>

    <h3>Method 2: Move the Decimal and Adjust</h3>
    <p>This method works everywhere and is dead simple:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Move the decimal point one place to the left. That gives you <strong>10%</strong>.</li>
      <li>For <strong>15%</strong>, add half of that number to itself. ($54 bill → 10% is $5.40 → half is $2.70 → 15% is $8.10.)</li>
      <li>For <strong>20%</strong>, just double the 10% number. ($54 bill → 10% is $5.40 → 20% is $10.80.)</li>
    </ol>
    <p>With practice, this takes about three seconds.</p>

    <h2>Pre-Tax vs. Post-Tax Tipping</h2>
    <p>Etiquette experts say you should tip on the <strong>pre-tax subtotal</strong> — the cost of the food and drinks before sales tax is added. In practice, the difference is small. On a $80 meal with 8% tax ($86.40 total), a 20% tip on the pre-tax amount is $16.00, and on the post-tax amount it is $17.28. Most people simply tip on whatever total they see, and no server will complain either way.</p>

    <h2>Should You Tip on Takeout?</h2>
    <p>Takeout tipping was uncommon before 2020, but attitudes have shifted. A tip of <strong>10% to 15%</strong> is now considered polite for takeout orders, particularly at independent restaurants. Staff still package your food, check the order for accuracy, and include condiments and utensils. If you can afford it, leaving a few dollars is a kind thing to do — but it is not the strong social obligation that a sit-down tip is.</p>

    <AdUnit slot="blog-mid" format="horizontal" />

    <h2>How to Handle Poor Service</h2>
    <p>Leaving zero is a drastic statement, and before you do it, consider whether the problem was actually your server's fault. A long wait for food is usually a kitchen issue, not a service issue. If the server was rude, inattentive, or genuinely negligent, dropping to 10% sends a clear signal. Leaving nothing should be reserved for truly terrible experiences.</p>
    <p>If you have a problem, speak to a manager. That actually gets results. A missing tip just costs your server money without addressing the issue.</p>

    <h2>Group Dining and Automatic Gratuity</h2>
    <p>Many restaurants add an <strong>automatic gratuity of 18% to 20%</strong> for parties of six or more. This is legal, standard, and should be stated on the menu. Before you add a tip on top, check the bill carefully — the line labeled "Gratuity" or "Service Charge" means the tip is already included.</p>
    <p>When splitting the bill among friends, make sure the total tips add up to at least 18–20% of the original bill. A common mistake is for each person to tip on their individual split, which sometimes results in an undertip because of rounding.</p>

    <h2>When You Do Not Need to Tip</h2>
    <p>Not every transaction requires a tip. You are not expected to tip:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>At fast-food counters where there is no table service</li>
      <li>Retail store employees</li>
      <li>Doctors, dentists, or other medical professionals</li>
      <li>Government workers (mail carriers are an exception during the holidays)</li>
      <li>Business owners who set their own prices and perform the service themselves (though it is still welcome)</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Final Thoughts</h2>
    <p>Tipping does not have to be stressful. For most situations, 20% is the easy, generous default. Move the decimal, double it, and you are done. When in doubt, tip. The few extra dollars matter far more to the person receiving them than they do to you.</p>

